Managed Kubernetes (Amazon EKS) Integration with Jenkins
We integrate Jenkins with Amazon EKS so Jenkins can deploy application manifests to the Kubernetes cluster after a successful build.
1. Create an Amazon EKS Cluster
  - Create the EKS cluster.
  - Create worker nodes (Managed Node Group).
2. Install kubectl on Jenkins Agent
  - Install kubectl.
  - Verify installation:
    kubectl version --client
3. Configure AWS CLI
  - Install AWS CLI on the Jenkins Agent.
  - Configure AWS credentials:
    aws configure
4. Connect Jenkins to EKS
  - Update the kubeconfig file:
    aws eks update-kubeconfig --region <region> --name <cluster-name>
  - Verify the connection:
    kubectl get nodes
5. Install Required Tools
  - Install Git.
  - Install Docker.
  - Install kubectl.
  - Install AWS CLI.
6. Store AWS Credentials in Jenkins
  - Manage Jenkins → Credentials
  - Add AWS Access Key ID and Secret Access Key.
7. Configure Jenkins Pipeline
  - Use the stored AWS credentials.
  - Execute kubectl commands or update the Kubernetes manifests.
  - Push manifest changes to the GitHub Manifest Repository (GitOps).
8. Deployment
  - ArgoCD monitors the Manifest Repository.
  - Detects the updated image tag.
  - Automatically synchronizes the changes.
  - Deploys the application to the Amazon EKS cluster.
9. Verify Deployment
  - Check cluster nodes:
    kubectl get nodes
  - Check pods:
    kubectl get pods -n <namespace>
  - Check services:
    kubectl get svc -n <namespace>
